############################################################ # Header ############################################################ TEXT(beginproblem());
############################################################ # PG Setup Code ############################################################ $xi = RadioButtons( ["A) the cost of the TV ads.", "B) the best number of TV ads.", "C) the most TV ads she can buy for the money.", "D) the average number of TV ads."], 2 ); $yi = RadioButtons( ["A) the cost of the radio ads.", "B) the number of radio ads she bought", "C) the number of radio ads if no TV ads are bought.", "D) the average cost per ad."], 2 );
Context("Point"); $x0=20; $y0=60; $xint = Point($x0,0); $yint = Point(0,$y0);
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML a. Enter each intercept as an ordered pair.
The [`x`]-intercept is [_]{$xint}{4}.
The [`y`]-intercept is [_]{$yint}{4}.
a. What do the intercepts tell us about the problem?
The [`x`]-intercept tells us:
[_]{$xi}{5}
The [`y`]-intercept tells us:
[_]{$yi}{5}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION a. We find the [`x`]-intercept by setting [`y=0`] and solving for [`x`] to learn that [`x=[$x0]\text{,}`] so the [`x`]-intercept is [`[$xint]\text{.}`]
We find the [`y`]-intercept by setting [`x=0`] and solving for [`y`] to learn that [`y=[$y0]\text{,}`] so the [`y`]-intercept is [`[$yint]\text{.}`]
a. The [`x`]-intercept has [`y=0\text{,}`] that is, it corresponds to when there are zero radio ads. The [`y`]-intercept has [`x=0\text{,}`] that is, it corresponds to when there are zero tv ads.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
